The Sn-P phase diagram has three known phases (Zavrazhnova, 2018): \begin{itemize} \item \href{current_web_home_dir/A3B_hR8_166_h_c-001}{SnP$_{3}$} \item \href{current_web_home_dir/A3B4_hR7_166_ac_2c-002}{Sn$_{4}$P$_{3}$} \item \href{current_web_home_dir/A16B3_hR19_166_2c2h_ac-001}{Sn$_{3}$P$_{4}$} (this structure) \end{itemize} ~ \vspace{-.25in} 
 While the tin sites are fully occupied, the phosphorous sites of Sn$_{3}$P$_{4}$ are highly disordered: \begin{itemize} \item The P I (2c) site is 24\% occupied. \item The P II (2c) site is 22.2\% occupied. \item The P III (6h) site is 26.1\% occupied. \item The P IV (6h) site is 25.6\% occupied. \end{itemize} ~ \vspace{-.25in} 
 These partial occupations give the observed stoichiometry. 
 Hexagonal settings of this structure can be obtained with the option {\tt --hex}.
